WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.280
 - Hello and welcome to C Programming for Everybody.

00:00:02.280 --> 00:00:05.860
 I'm Charles Severance and I'm your professor for this course.

00:00:05.860 --> 00:00:10.860
 In this lecture, we are going to do a very rapid translation

00:00:10.860 --> 00:00:12.460
 from Python to C.

00:00:12.460 --> 00:00:15.740
 So as I've shown you in our earlier lectures,

00:00:15.740 --> 00:00:18.120
 C is kind of like the mother tongue

00:00:18.120 --> 00:00:20.400
 of advanced programming languages.

00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:23.440
 Python itself was written and still is written in C.

00:00:23.440 --> 00:00:25.900
 And Python is deeply influenced by C,

00:00:25.900 --> 00:00:28.880
 even though the syntax looks very different, right?

00:00:30.120 --> 00:00:32.380
 And if you've taken all my other classes,

00:00:32.380 --> 00:00:35.720
 you will have seen PHP, you'll have seen JavaScript.

00:00:35.720 --> 00:00:40.080
 And to some degree, even CSS takes some of its inspiration

00:00:40.080 --> 00:00:42.100
 from the syntax of C.

00:00:42.100 --> 00:00:45.200
 And so I'm not intending for this

00:00:45.200 --> 00:00:46.740
 to be your first programming class.

00:00:46.740 --> 00:00:49.280
 I intend for you to be an expert at Python.

00:00:49.280 --> 00:00:51.400
 Well, not expert, but certainly,

00:00:51.400 --> 00:00:52.880
 I'm not gonna tell you what an if statement is.

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:55.080
 I'm not gonna tell you what a variable is.

00:00:55.080 --> 00:00:56.980
 I'm gonna just tell you how to use variables in C

00:00:56.980 --> 00:00:58.680
 and I'm gonna tell you how to use if statements in C.

00:00:58.680 --> 00:01:01.720
 And so that's why a solid foundation of Python,

00:01:01.720 --> 00:01:05.200
 not wizard, but solid foundation of Python is essential.

00:01:05.200 --> 00:01:08.560
 And frankly, I would rather that you learned a bit of PHP,

00:01:08.560 --> 00:01:13.420
 some JavaScript, and all this other stuff before you come.

00:01:13.420 --> 00:01:16.300
 I think that C programming is not the first class

00:01:16.300 --> 00:01:18.600
 that you should take, but instead,

00:01:18.600 --> 00:01:21.760
 it is your gateway to the advanced work

00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:22.600
 that you're going to do.

00:01:22.600 --> 00:01:24.360
 And so I think C is very, very important.

00:01:24.360 --> 00:01:27.480
 I just don't think it's your first programming class.

00:01:27.480 --> 00:01:31.760
 So, you might think Python and C are not very different,

00:01:31.760 --> 00:01:35.460
 although Python is written in C.

00:01:35.460 --> 00:01:38.680
 Python has whitespace that is part of its syntax.

00:01:38.680 --> 00:01:41.220
 C whitespace is ignored.

00:01:41.220 --> 00:01:43.520
 I do like C better in that.

00:01:43.520 --> 00:01:45.920
 Python is very object oriented.

00:01:45.920 --> 00:01:48.740
 If you read an article I wrote on Quora,

00:01:48.740 --> 00:01:50.800
 you'll see I rank all my languages

00:01:50.800 --> 00:01:53.160
 and I put JavaScript and Python

00:01:53.160 --> 00:01:55.720
 as the most object oriented languages.

00:01:55.720 --> 00:01:57.440
 Java is a little less object oriented

00:01:57.440 --> 00:02:00.520
 and C is like the least un-object oriented.

00:02:00.520 --> 00:02:02.400
 C is not object oriented at all.

00:02:02.400 --> 00:02:06.540
 Python has wonderfully convenient data structures

00:02:06.540 --> 00:02:08.320
 in the form of lists and dictionaries.

00:02:08.320 --> 00:02:13.320
 PHP has arrays and JavaScript has objects,

00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:15.720
 the all beautiful, beautiful stuff.

00:02:15.720 --> 00:02:17.740
 They're very object oriented structures.

00:02:17.740 --> 00:02:19.400
 Python, C does not.

00:02:19.400 --> 00:02:21.520
 It's fast, it's efficient, it's powerful,

00:02:21.520 --> 00:02:22.960
 it's got structs and pointers,

00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:25.520
 and by golly, you will use them

00:02:25.520 --> 00:02:28.160
 and they're not convenient,

00:02:28.160 --> 00:02:30.280
 but they are scorchingly fast.

00:02:30.280 --> 00:02:32.760
 And by the time we're done with all this,

00:02:32.760 --> 00:02:36.780
 we will see how to use structs and pointers

00:02:36.780 --> 00:02:38.700
 to build lists and dictionaries.

00:02:38.700 --> 00:02:42.640
 And that really is, we will follow down the path

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:43.600
 of building Python.

00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:46.560
 So you'll see a common theme throughout this class

00:02:46.560 --> 00:02:50.540
 of how Python achieves what it's trying to achieve

00:02:50.540 --> 00:02:51.760
 by writing C.

00:02:51.760 --> 00:02:54.860
 Python has automatic memory management

00:02:54.860 --> 00:02:57.520
 to the point where if you've been a Python programmer,

00:02:57.520 --> 00:03:00.000
 or a PHP programmer, or a Java programmer,

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:00.840
 or a JavaScript programmer,

00:03:00.840 --> 00:03:03.840
 you probably don't even know what memory management is.

00:03:03.840 --> 00:03:06.080
 Well, you're going to by the end of this class.

00:03:06.080 --> 00:03:08.080
 And by the end of this class,

00:03:08.080 --> 00:03:11.520
 you're going to be able to see how Python

00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:14.900
 automates memory management for you, right?

00:03:14.900 --> 00:03:16.360
 Python is written in the 80s,

00:03:16.360 --> 00:03:18.040
 and C was written in the 70s.

00:03:18.040 --> 00:03:22.580
 In many ways, I see Python as a convenience layer

00:03:22.580 --> 00:03:24.920
 that was built on top of C.

00:03:24.920 --> 00:03:27.880
 Just, C programmers look at C, it's like,

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:29.100
 it's great, it's great, it's great.

00:03:29.100 --> 00:03:33.640
 If we just had this layer of easiness on top of it,

00:03:33.640 --> 00:03:34.960
 then things would be better.

00:03:34.960 --> 00:03:37.460
 And so, that's what Python is.

00:03:37.460 --> 00:03:40.700
 Now, Python also introduced things like

00:03:40.700 --> 00:03:44.200
 quite different syntax to make it indentation

00:03:44.200 --> 00:03:48.960
 required, because they thought it was a good idea.

00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:51.720
 So we could argue one way or the other.

00:03:51.720 --> 00:03:52.640
 I mean, I'll tell you,

00:03:52.640 --> 00:03:55.740
 when I'm writing a million lines of code,

00:03:55.740 --> 00:03:58.720
 white space is not, to me, a good way to have syntax.

00:03:58.720 --> 00:04:02.320
 So, we're going to look at C through a Python lens.

00:04:02.320 --> 00:04:05.020
 And we're going to learn by example.

00:04:05.020 --> 00:04:07.940
 Now, most of the time, I tell you,

