 Constants, about the only thing

00:07:50.920 --> 00:07:53.520
 that's really different in constants

00:07:53.520 --> 00:07:56.280
 is like strings and characters and booleans.

00:07:56.280 --> 00:07:58.780
 And strings and characters are like the biggest thing

00:07:58.780 --> 00:08:00.400
 in the beginning.

00:08:00.400 --> 00:08:04.160
 Both have int and float and char and byte.

00:08:04.160 --> 00:08:08.220
 Now, again, byte and string and char are not the same thing.

00:08:08.220 --> 00:08:11.320
 C has no str class, which is the string class,

00:08:11.320 --> 00:08:12.720
 list or dictionary.

00:08:12.720 --> 00:08:15.440
 And Python has no concept of struct or double.

00:08:15.440 --> 00:08:18.800
 And in a sense, you could think of Python's float

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:20.880
 as really C's double, right?

00:08:20.880 --> 00:08:23.740
 And so, by the time Python was written,

00:08:23.740 --> 00:08:26.520
 the notion of shorter floating point numbers

00:08:26.520 --> 00:08:28.220
 is less critical.

00:08:28.220 --> 00:08:30.360
 There are some differences.

00:08:30.360 --> 00:08:33.700
 A lot of this, I think, was in the design of Python,

00:08:33.700 --> 00:08:35.920
 trying to be a little less obtuse and a little more

00:08:35.920 --> 00:08:37.000
 convenient.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:38.200
 For me, it's annoying.

00:08:38.200 --> 00:08:40.320
 I write the C versions of the operators,

00:08:40.320 --> 00:08:43.920
 like and, double ampersand, not is exclamation point,

00:08:43.920 --> 00:08:47.080
 we call that bang, or double vertical bar.

00:08:47.080 --> 00:08:50.080
 And in Python, they're all convenient.

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:52.680
 We use the word A and B, but okay, whatever.

00:08:52.680 --> 00:08:57.740
 So there, in C, we have a for loop,

00:08:57.740 --> 00:08:59.660
 but it's an indeterminate loop,

00:08:59.660 --> 00:09:02.120
 if you remember the definition from Python for everybody.

00:09:02.120 --> 00:09:04.120
 Indeterminate loop is one that you have to examine

00:09:04.120 --> 00:09:05.560
 to see if it's got an infinite loop.

00:09:05.560 --> 00:09:10.560
 Whereas in Python, if you say for x in some list,

00:09:10.560 --> 00:09:12.680
 you're gonna go through the whole list.

00:09:12.680 --> 00:09:13.800
 It's a determinant loop.

00:09:13.800 --> 00:09:16.920
 It only runs until that list is exhausted.

00:09:16.920 --> 00:09:19.280
 C does not have such a thing, right?

00:09:19.280 --> 00:09:22.680
 It just, every loop has got a condition to finish it.

00:09:22.680 --> 00:09:25.700
 Now we write loops like for i equals one to 100,

00:09:25.700 --> 00:09:27.640
 or zero to 99.

00:09:27.640 --> 00:09:29.200
 We write them, and you can look at them and say,

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:30.420
 yeah, that's not an infinite loop.

00:09:30.420 --> 00:09:33.120
 It's just, technically, you have to look at the loop

00:09:33.120 --> 00:09:35.480
 to make sure that you haven't inadvertently

00:09:35.480 --> 00:09:37.500
 made an infinite loop.

00:09:37.500 --> 00:09:39.360
 There's no predefined true and false.

00:09:39.360 --> 00:09:41.640
 I find this really like, wow, couldn't they,

00:09:41.640 --> 00:09:45.200
 they got EOF, capital EOF for end of file in C.

