 in the C that you're using,

00:12:20.360 --> 00:12:21.940
 but I'm kinda being kinda strict,

00:12:21.940 --> 00:12:24.640
 and so I'm pretending I'm in 1978,

00:12:24.640 --> 00:12:28.240
 so I'm not using that C++ style comment.

00:12:28.240 --> 00:12:32.080
 Again, that came from C++, it didn't come from JavaScript.

00:12:32.080 --> 00:12:33.800
 Some of you have taken Python classes

00:12:33.800 --> 00:12:36.060
 where there's this like underscore underscore main,

00:12:36.060 --> 00:12:38.040
 and it calls this thing, and it makes a function,

00:12:38.040 --> 00:12:41.340
 and calls it, and indents everything one tab,

00:12:41.340 --> 00:12:44.480
 and they're really imitating C in that respect.

00:12:44.480 --> 00:12:46.940
 And I think, I don't like that style.

00:12:46.940 --> 00:12:49.920
 I think those people who do that in Python,

00:12:49.920 --> 00:12:52.000
 I'm sure they have a good reason,

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:56.040
 but I think they're just like wishing it was C.

00:12:56.040 --> 00:12:59.000
 'Cause the definition of C is the code,

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:01.820
 a program starts, when it starts running,

00:13:01.820 --> 00:13:05.280
 it searches for a function named main,

00:13:05.280 --> 00:13:06.600
 and later we'll see that this function

00:13:06.600 --> 00:13:08.520
 can actually have arguments,

00:13:08.520 --> 00:13:11.200
 and it returns an integer as to the success or failure.

00:13:11.200 --> 00:13:14.480
 So really, main is a function.

00:13:14.480 --> 00:13:16.080
 And so that first line there,

00:13:16.080 --> 00:13:19.360
 int main open paren close paren open curly brace,

00:13:19.360 --> 00:13:21.540
 that is the definition of a function

00:13:21.540 --> 00:13:23.740
 that happens to be named main.

00:13:23.740 --> 00:13:26.920
 And then we have printf.

00:13:26.920 --> 00:13:31.500
 Now, again, I don't know if you've learned Python 2,

00:13:31.500 --> 00:13:34.360
 but in Python 2, there was a print statement.

00:13:34.360 --> 00:13:38.240
 In Python 3, there is a print function,

00:13:38.240 --> 00:13:41.420
 and so here we're using a Python 3 print function,

00:13:41.420 --> 00:13:45.440
 and C never did the statement.

00:13:45.440 --> 00:13:48.800
 So C decided, as we'll talk about later,

00:13:48.800 --> 00:13:51.640
 to not have any input/output,

00:13:51.640 --> 00:13:54.960
 any reading or writing in the language itself,

00:13:54.960 --> 00:13:57.360
 but instead put them in standard libraries.

00:13:57.360 --> 00:14:01.160
 And that's what this pound includes, stdio.h is saying,

00:14:01.160 --> 00:14:04.440
 okay, I'm gonna do some IO here, input/output here,

00:14:04.440 --> 00:14:08.240
 and so include the C input/output library.

00:14:08.240 --> 00:14:13.240
 Okay, and so printf takes as its first parameter a string.

00:14:13.240 --> 00:14:15.640
 The other thing you see in C

00:14:15.640 --> 00:14:19.080
 is you can't use single quotes for long strings.

00:14:19.080 --> 00:14:20.300
 Later we'll see single quotes,

00:14:20.300 --> 00:14:22.760
 but in C there's a major difference

00:14:22.760 --> 00:14:25.280
 between single quotes and double quotes.

00:14:25.280 --> 00:14:27.840
 Single quotes are single characters,

00:14:27.840 --> 00:14:30.720
 and double quotes are a character array.

00:14:30.720 --> 00:14:33.800
 Not a string, character array.

00:14:33.800 --> 00:14:36.280
 The other thing is things like the end of line.

00:14:36.280 --> 00:14:40.840
 So in Python, the new line is added implicitly.

00:14:40.840 --> 00:14:43.620
 In C, you have to add it explicitly.

00:14:43.620 --> 00:14:46.880
 And so that's basically saying print hello world,

00:14:46.880 --> 00:14:49.200
 and then go to the beginning of the next line.

00:14:49.200 --> 00:14:52.840
 Now, this first parameter is actually not just a string.

00:14:52.840 --> 00:14:56.120
 It's a string with embedded format codes

00:14:56.120 --> 00:14:58.200
 that start with percent.

00:14:58.200 --> 00:15:03.200
 Percent D says there is a corresponding integer number,

00:15:03.200 --> 00:15:08.280
 and I want you to convert that into a string

00:15:08.280 --> 00:15:09.620
 and print it out.

00:15:09.620 --> 00:15:12.800
 I guess I should probably just re-array some of this.

00:15:12.800 --> 00:15:16.220
 So it says answer, and then a number.

00:15:16.220 --> 00:15:21.040
 And so you can have more than one of these things,

00:15:21.040 --> 00:15:22.320
 and then they match.

00:15:22.320 --> 00:15:25.220
 So that says there's an integer as another parameter.

00:15:25.220 --> 00:15:28.600
 So you can have one parameter, two parameters, et cetera.

00:15:28.600 --> 00:15:32.280
 So for beyond one parameter, like in this one,

00:15:32.280 --> 00:15:34.920
 X percent dot one F,

00:15:34.920 --> 00:15:37.220
 that corresponds to this first floating point number,

00:15:37.220 --> 00:15:40.940
 and this percent D corresponds to the integer one, okay?

00:15:40.940 --> 00:15:42.640
 So you have these percent things.

00:15:42.640 --> 00:15:45.680
 Now, we will learn that these percent things

00:15:45.680 --> 00:15:50.680
 have a language unto themselves in chapter eight.

00:15:50.680 --> 00:15:53.480
 And this is basically saying,

00:15:53.480 --> 00:15:55.720
 please print me a floating point number

00:15:55.720 --> 00:15:58.480
 with only one digit of precision, right?

00:15:58.480 --> 00:16:03.180
 So percent dot one F says print a floating point number.

00:16:03.180 --> 00:16:06.840
 And then if we wanna string, it's percent S,

00:16:06.840 --> 00:16:10.520
 but this really, Sarah here, double quote Sarah, double quote,

00:16:10.520 --> 00:16:12.960
 is a character array.

00:16:12.960 --> 00:16:17.120
 And it's actually not five characters, but six,

00:16:17.120 --> 00:16:20.080
 because there is always a terminating zero character

00:16:20.080 --> 00:16:20.920
 at the end.

00:16:20.920 --> 00:16:24.640
 And so percent S says the parameter needs to be

00:16:24.640 --> 00:16:28.280
 a character array and properly terminated

00:16:28.280 --> 00:16:32.280
 by an end to string indicator, which is a zero character.

00:16:32.280 --> 00:16:35.880
 So that's this, right?

00:16:35.880 --> 00:16:37.600
 It's pretty simple,

00:16:37.600 --> 00:16:40.560
 but we've got a lot of stuff to cover here.

00:16:40.560 --> 00:16:42.800
 And this is the Rosetta Stone.

00:16:42.800 --> 00:16:45.920
 It's more complex in C, you have more control,

00:16:45.920 --> 00:16:48.560
 you're doing things more explicitly,

00:16:48.560 --> 00:16:52.180
 and it's not doing it for you automatically.

00:16:52.180 --> 00:16:55.760
 So let's take a look at a simple number input.

00:16:55.760 --> 00:16:58.160
 Now you'll see that some of these things come from

00:16:58.160 --> 00:17:01.020
 my Python for everybody class.

00:17:01.020 --> 00:17:06.020
 This is the famous US floor to European floor elevator,

00:17:06.020 --> 00:17:07.520
 converter.

00:17:07.520 --> 00:17:09.780
 So we're gonna print something out.

00:17:09.780 --> 00:17:14.720
 Now one thing about C is that you've got to declare

00:17:14.720 --> 00:17:16.620
 all your variables.

00:17:16.620 --> 00:17:18.660
 Python is sort of a typeless language.

00:17:18.660 --> 00:17:21.520
 It's increasingly getting more typey,

00:17:21.520 --> 00:17:23.920
 but it's a typeless language.

00:17:23.920 --> 00:17:26.860
 So we have to declare that we're gonna have two variables,

00:17:26.860 --> 00:17:29.700
 USF and EUF, and they're gonna be integers.

00:17:29.700 --> 00:17:33.120
 We print the statement, but the only difference there

00:17:33.120 --> 00:17:34.760
 is we have to put the backslash n in,

00:17:34.760 --> 00:17:37.000
 otherwise it won't automatically do that.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:39.240
 And then we have this IO routine, again,

00:17:39.240 --> 00:17:42.320
 coming from stdio.h, called scanf.

00:17:42.320 --> 00:17:44.640
 And its first parameter, much like printf,

00:17:44.640 --> 00:17:46.400
 is actually a formatting string.

00:17:46.400 --> 00:17:48.800
 And what this says is this says,

00:17:48.800 --> 00:17:52.080
 read four little ways, find me a number,

00:17:52.080 --> 00:17:53.880
 as long as it seems like a number, keep reading,

00:17:53.880 --> 00:17:56.000
 and turn that into an integer and give it back to me.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:59.800
 And so it actually has got some scanning built into it.

00:17:59.800 --> 00:18:02.680
 And it reads until it finds a non-digit,

00:18:02.680 --> 00:18:04.360
 and then stops and says that's the number.

00:18:04.360 --> 00:18:07.480
 So it turns out, in C, the way,

00:18:07.480 --> 00:18:09.720
 you could type a lot of different things here.

00:18:09.720 --> 00:18:11.400
 We won't go into that in too much detail.

00:18:11.400 --> 00:18:12.840
 We'll hold that until chapter eight.

00:18:12.840 --> 00:18:16.380
 But the idea is it doesn't work exactly the same,

00:18:16.380 --> 00:18:20.120
 although this input in Python reads a line.

00:18:20.120 --> 00:18:22.480
 Now, again, I got this little note here.

00:18:22.480 --> 00:18:26.520
 If you recall, if you recall, in Python 2,

00:18:26.520 --> 00:18:28.400
 there was an input and a raw input.

00:18:28.400 --> 00:18:30.280
 And raw input was what read a line,

00:18:30.280 --> 00:18:33.040
 which I tended to use when I was teaching Python 2.

00:18:34.280 --> 00:18:36.280
 Input was a weird thing that had

00:18:36.280 --> 00:18:38.240
 some kind of scanning thing going on,

00:18:38.240 --> 00:18:39.920
 and it scanned and threw stuff away,

00:18:39.920 --> 00:18:40.960
 and it grabbed something,

00:18:40.960 --> 00:18:43.040
 and it might go to multiple lines.

00:18:43.040 --> 00:18:46.840
 And it was totally inconsistent,

00:18:46.840 --> 00:18:49.160
 and it was worse than scanf.

00:18:49.160 --> 00:18:52.520
 So I was really glad when they just got rid of it

00:18:52.520 --> 00:18:55.800
 in Python 3, and then they changed the name.

00:18:55.800 --> 00:18:57.600
 What used to be Python 2's raw input

00:18:57.600 --> 00:19:00.200
 became input in Python 3.

00:19:00.200 --> 00:19:04.880
 So the old input from Python 2 is kind of like homage

00:19:04.880 --> 00:19:09.120
 to scanf in C, but it's not exactly the same.

00:19:09.120 --> 00:19:11.840
 And the reason it's not the same is

00:19:11.840 --> 00:19:18.900
 the input in Python 2 was deriving the type of the data

00:19:18.900 --> 00:19:20.060
 from what it encountered.

00:19:20.060 --> 00:19:21.480
 So it might give you back a string,

00:19:21.480 --> 00:19:22.880
 it might give you back a floating point,

00:19:22.880 --> 00:19:24.880
 it might go like, ooh, that's dangerous, right?

00:19:24.880 --> 00:19:28.960
 And that's because the type of USF in Python here

00:19:28.960 --> 00:19:32.840
 is determined, it's not pre-declared.

00:19:32.840 --> 00:19:36.220
 So it's known because we're gonna convert it to an integer.

00:19:36.220 --> 00:19:40.400
 And by the way, both the input and the scanf,

00:19:40.400 --> 00:19:42.560
 we can write stuff that confuses it badly

00:19:42.560 --> 00:19:43.700
 and causes it to blow up,

00:19:43.700 --> 00:19:47.360
 but we're not worrying too much about that right now.

00:19:47.360 --> 00:19:49.040
 We're just kinda getting the basics done.

00:19:49.040 --> 00:19:52.320
 So we read an integer, we subtract one,

00:19:52.320 --> 00:19:54.320
 we print it out, right?

00:19:54.320 --> 00:19:58.360
 We read an integer, oh, I forgot to say this ampersand.

00:19:59.160 --> 00:20:01.120
 Call by reference and call by value.

00:20:01.120 --> 00:20:04.800
 So in Python, this is coming back as a function return,

00:20:04.800 --> 00:20:07.280
 so it's really easy to assign it into USF.

00:20:07.280 --> 00:20:12.280
 Whereas in C, we put these parameters on scanf call,

00:20:12.280 --> 00:20:15.560
 and we have to say, oh, and by the way,

00:20:15.560 --> 00:20:16.720
 I want you to change it.

00:20:16.720 --> 00:20:21.080
 Because ultimately, if we don't put ampersand on,

00:20:21.080 --> 00:20:23.880
 it's what's called call by value, not call by reference.

00:20:23.880 --> 00:20:27.200
 And ampersand USF is a way to tell C

00:20:27.200 --> 00:20:31.140
 to actually give it the address of the USF variable

00:20:31.140 --> 00:20:33.480
 rather than the value in the USF variable.

00:20:33.480 --> 00:20:38.320
 And in that is a whole chapter that we will cover,

00:20:38.320 --> 00:20:40.480
 like I think four and five,

00:20:40.480 --> 00:20:44.000
 will be all about the ampersand and call by reference.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:45.560
 And call by, we're way ahead,

00:20:45.560 --> 00:20:47.880
 'cause I don't think chapters one through four would,

00:20:47.880 --> 00:20:49.640
 all they ever do is mention call by reference

00:20:49.640 --> 00:20:52.960
 and then say, oh, that's in the future.

00:20:52.960 --> 00:20:55.480
 So I'm gonna just say, oh, that's in the future.

00:20:55.480 --> 00:20:58.720
 I will tell you that that ampersand is really important

00:20:58.720 --> 00:21:00.240
 and the code doesn't work without it

00:21:00.240 --> 00:21:04.200
 because it is the way that C does call by reference

00:21:04.200 --> 00:21:07.060
 for simple variables like integers and floats.

00:21:07.060 --> 00:21:10.200
 As you're gonna see on the next slide,

00:21:10.200 --> 00:21:11.640
 there's always an exception.

00:21:11.640 --> 00:21:16.620
 String input, okay.

00:21:16.620 --> 00:21:18.800
 So here we're gonna, this is a help my hello Sarah thing,

00:21:18.800 --> 00:21:21.980
 right, we say enter your name and then we say name input.

00:21:21.980 --> 00:21:24.020
 Now the beauty is here in Python

00:21:24.020 --> 00:21:26.920
 is input gives us a whole line, okay.

00:21:26.920 --> 00:21:28.680
 And then we just print hello name

00:21:28.680 --> 00:21:30.600
 and you'll notice that there's like this little space

00:21:30.600 --> 00:21:32.880
 that comes out automatically.

00:21:32.880 --> 00:21:36.320
 So switching over to C, we have our included library,

00:21:36.320 --> 00:21:38.880
 we have the int main, which is the,

00:21:38.880 --> 00:21:42.000
 and then we have to pre-declare a character array.

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:44.400
 There is no like, make it a string.

00:21:44.400 --> 00:21:46.320
 If this were Python, we could say,

00:21:46.320 --> 00:21:49.200
 hey, let's make a string, but you can't.

00:21:49.200 --> 00:21:50.460
 And what's even more important

00:21:50.460 --> 00:21:52.580
 is you gotta tell it how long,

00:21:52.580 --> 00:21:55.200
 which means that we could type too much stuff in here

00:21:55.200 --> 00:21:56.360
 and blow our program up.

00:21:56.360 --> 00:21:58.760
 And that's one of the difficulties of C

00:21:58.760 --> 00:22:01.720
 is the fact that arrays, including character arrays,

00:22:01.720 --> 00:22:04.200
 have fixed length and they don't auto-extend.

00:22:04.200 --> 00:22:09.200
 There is no, there is no dot append in C.

00:22:09.200 --> 00:22:13.340
 You can't like say, oh, name dot append, you can't do it.

00:22:13.340 --> 00:22:16.720
 Python, it's an object, it's not an actual array.

00:22:16.720 --> 00:22:17.800
 Python, it's an object.

00:22:17.800 --> 00:22:19.360
 Name is a string object.

00:22:19.360 --> 00:22:22.280
 Here, name is a character array with 100 elements

00:22:22.280 --> 00:22:24.360
 and if you put 20 in, you'll be fine.

00:22:24.360 --> 00:22:25.840
 If you put 80 in, you'll be fine.

00:22:25.840 --> 00:22:28.280
 If you put 101 in, it's gonna blow up.

00:22:28.280 --> 00:22:31.040
 Ah, well, that's okay.

00:22:31.040 --> 00:22:32.940
 That's why C is fast.

00:22:32.940 --> 00:22:34.840
 We'll get to all that, we'll get to all that.

00:22:34.840 --> 00:22:37.100
 So we print out a prompt and we say scanf

00:22:37.100 --> 00:22:40.860
 and we say, in this case, %s, give me a string,

00:22:40.860 --> 00:22:42.560
 and you can put a limit on it.

00:22:42.560 --> 00:22:46.520
 So we're saying, look, only read up to 100 characters.

00:22:46.520 --> 00:22:49.480
 And you'll notice there is no ampersand on name

00:22:49.480 --> 00:22:52.220
 and that is because name is an array.

00:22:52.220 --> 00:22:56.280
 And so when you put name in with no square brackets,

00:22:56.280 --> 00:23:00.280
 no index operator, then you're passing the address

00:23:00.280 --> 00:23:01.760
 of the beginning of the array.

00:23:01.760 --> 00:23:05.400
 And so that is, in a sense, an ampersand.

00:23:05.400 --> 00:23:07.040
 That is the location of the beginning

00:23:07.040 --> 00:23:09.040
 of a 100-character array.

00:23:09.040 --> 00:23:11.400
 We're gonna scan up to 100 characters into it

00:23:11.400 --> 00:23:15.560
 and so it really is roughly equivalent to the input.

00:23:15.560 --> 00:23:19.120
 And then we just, again, say, hello, %s

00:23:19.120 --> 00:23:21.360
 and then name is the corresponding thing.

00:23:21.360 --> 00:23:24.280
 And so it says, hello, Sarah.

00:23:24.280 --> 00:23:26.440
 Now a lot of what we did in the Python for everybody

00:23:26.440 --> 00:23:28.000
 is read whole lines of input.

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:30.800
 And we tended to use string parsing of those lines,

00:23:30.800 --> 00:23:32.460
 like we would trim the stuff off the end

00:23:32.460 --> 00:23:34.320
 and then we'd split it and do all these things.

00:23:34.320 --> 00:23:36.580
 And there's no good split in C.

00:23:36.580 --> 00:23:38.360
 So we won't be doing too much of that,

00:23:38.360 --> 00:23:40.280
 but it does help to understand

00:23:40.280 --> 00:23:41.960
 how to read a whole line of input.

00:23:41.960 --> 00:23:44.080
 So now we're gonna read something that doesn't have,

00:23:44.080 --> 00:23:46.320
 it has lots of spaces, we're gonna read the whole line

00:23:46.320 --> 00:23:48.660
 and we're just gonna echo the whole line, right?

00:23:48.660 --> 00:23:51.160
 Enter line, read the line, print the line.

00:23:51.160 --> 00:23:53.040
 So now we're gonna have, again,

00:23:53.040 --> 00:23:56.760
 we have to declare how big of a string we're willing to take,

00:23:56.760 --> 00:24:01.240
 char line with 1,000 characters in it.

00:24:01.240 --> 00:24:03.720
 The prompt by now should be pretty easy

00:24:03.720 --> 00:24:06.240
 and we have a really weird looking

00:24:06.240 --> 00:24:11.600
 % square bracket, caret, backslash,

00:24:11.600 --> 00:24:15.520
 and close square bracket, 1,000s.

00:24:15.520 --> 00:24:18.880
 Well, if you took Python for everybody

00:24:18.880 --> 00:24:21.520
 and you remember chapter 11, regular expressions,

00:24:21.520 --> 00:24:23.120
 that should look familiar to you.

00:24:23.120 --> 00:24:27.200
 Open bracket, caret, backslash, and close bracket

00:24:27.200 --> 00:24:30.600
 says match any character that's not a new line.

00:24:30.600 --> 00:24:34.840
 So that says scan up to the end of a line

00:24:34.840 --> 00:24:39.100
 or until you hit 1,000 characters.

00:24:39.100 --> 00:24:44.100
 Read a whole line, but stop at 1,000 characters.

00:24:44.120 --> 00:24:46.200
 And then, of course, a line is just a parameter

00:24:46.200 --> 00:24:48.360
 and then we print that thing out, okay?

00:24:48.360 --> 00:24:50.800
 And so a lot of C programmers probably never written

00:24:50.800 --> 00:24:54.240
 this particular line of code, but it gives you a sense

00:24:54.240 --> 00:24:57.680
 that there's a lot of sort of programmability

00:24:57.680 --> 00:25:02.640
 and things like regular expressions that Python had.

00:25:02.640 --> 00:25:04.540
 Well, those are kind of an old concept.

00:25:04.540 --> 00:25:07.000
 Those are seven 1970s concepts.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:12.000
 This C language had that concept in it in 1970.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:16.540
 There's another way that's a little safer to do this,

00:25:16.540 --> 00:25:18.200
 and these are the exact same thing

00:25:18.200 --> 00:25:20.700
 where this command fgit s.

00:25:20.700 --> 00:25:25.160
 So fgit s says put it into up to 1,000 characters,

00:25:25.160 --> 00:25:27.560
 looking for a new line, and reading

00:25:27.560 --> 00:25:28.880
 from what's called standard input.

00:25:28.880 --> 00:25:31.560
 So in C there are three basic files.

00:25:31.560 --> 00:25:32.880
 One is the standard input,

00:25:32.880 --> 00:25:36.000
 which usually is read up to EOF, standard output,

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:37.160
 which is where printf is going,

00:25:37.160 --> 00:25:39.480
 and then there's a thing called standard error,

00:25:39.480 --> 00:25:41.400
 which is where you send error messages

00:25:41.400 --> 00:25:43.120
 that you don't just wanna go to the output.

00:25:43.120 --> 00:25:45.000
